Summaries for PNPO Gene

Entrez Gene Summary for PNPO Gene

  • The enzyme encoded by this gene catalyzes the terminal, rate-limiting step in the synthesis of pyridoxal 5'-phosphate, also known as vitamin B6. Vitamin B6 is a required co-factor for enzymes involved in both homocysteine metabolism and synthesis of neurotransmitters such as catecholamine. Mutations in this gene result in pyridoxamine 5'-phosphate oxidase (PNPO) deficiency, a form of neonatal epileptic encephalopathy. [provided by RefSeq, Oct 2008]

GeneCards Summary for PNPO Gene

PNPO (Pyridoxamine 5'-Phosphate Oxidase) is a Protein Coding gene. Diseases associated with PNPO include pyridoxamine 5'-phosphate oxidase deficiency and pyridoxal phosphate-responsive seizures. Among its related pathways are Metabolism and Vitamin B6 metabolism. GO annotations related to this gene include oxidoreductase activity and oxidoreductase activity, acting on the CH-NH2 group of donors.

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot for PNPO Gene

  • PNPO_HUMAN,Q9NVS9

  • Catalyzes the oxidation of either pyridoxine 5-phosphate (PNP) or pyridoxamine 5-phosphate (PMP) into pyridoxal 5-phosphate (PLP).

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot

PNPO_HUMAN
  • Pyridoxine-5-phosphate oxidase deficiency (PNPO deficiency) [MIM:610090]: The main feature of neonatal epileptic encephalopathy is the onset within hours of birth of a severe seizure disorder that does not respond to anticonvulsant drugs and can be fatal. Seizures can cease with the administration of PLP, being resistant to treatment with pyridoxine,. {ECO:0000269 PubMed:15772097}. Note=The disease is caused by mutations affecting the gene represented in this entry.
